00:32:10.030 --> 00:32:12.490
that's really fascinating.

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:16.210
So before jumping
to that, to what you

00:32:16.210 --> 00:32:17.990
might see in a
previous life, let's

00:32:17.990 --> 00:32:20.660
talk about the idea
of previous lives.

00:32:20.660 --> 00:32:24.750
Because sound like you accept
it totally and everything.

00:32:24.750 --> 00:32:26.910
So this is a really
interesting, because I

00:32:26.910 --> 00:32:29.860
was born in a
Catholic household,

00:32:29.860 --> 00:32:32.160
and I never heard about
reincarnation before.

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:33.810
And it was only
until I went to India

00:32:33.810 --> 00:32:38.570
that I started hearing the word
reincarnation, here and there.

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:41.340
We would have lectures
from different teachers

00:32:41.340 --> 00:32:42.640
and they'd kind of mention it.

00:32:42.640 --> 00:32:47.060
But my interest in it, it
wasn't specifically profound.

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:50.140
And when I went
to Bhutan, they're

00:32:50.140 --> 00:32:53.350
really focused on happiness,
but it's a little bit punitive

00:32:53.350 --> 00:32:55.200
because one of their
focuses on happiness

00:32:55.200 --> 00:32:57.860
is because they believe
that you will reincarnate

00:32:57.860 --> 00:33:02.230
and that you have to be good so
that you will not have a lower

00:33:02.230 --> 00:33:04.040
reincarnation, if
that makes sense.

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:08.880
So they're very much this
idea that be a good person

00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:12.100
because you should be
a good person, but also

00:33:12.100 --> 00:33:15.014
because of option B, that
if you're not a good person

00:33:15.014 --> 00:33:16.930
and you come back, you
won't have a good life.

00:33:16.930 --> 00:33:22.080
And I was on the airplane,
flying to the Bhutan,

00:33:22.080 --> 00:33:26.180
and I was reading
the airline magazine.

00:33:26.180 --> 00:33:29.900
They had a whole article
about reincarnation.

00:33:29.900 --> 00:33:32.660
And there's another story,
which is when I was talking

00:33:32.660 --> 00:33:36.300
to this nun in the nunnery.

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:38.370
When I said, please
pray for husband,

00:33:38.370 --> 00:33:39.810
and she was flabbergasted.

00:33:39.810 --> 00:33:42.040
And it kind of just
left the anecdote there.

00:33:42.040 --> 00:33:44.405
But the conversation
actually continued.

00:33:44.405 --> 00:33:46.930
And she was flabbergasted
because she said,

00:33:46.930 --> 00:33:50.760
in my previous life, I prayed
so hard to be a monk because I

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:53.460
didn't want to be a wife
again, because I wanted

00:33:53.460 --> 00:33:56.580
to have this time so
that I could explore

00:33:56.580 --> 00:34:00.990
what it means to be human in
this world, is what she said.

00:34:00.990 --> 00:34:02.990
So when I came up on
this trip from Bhutan,

00:34:02.990 --> 00:34:05.470
I had a deeper interest
in reincarnation.

00:34:05.470 --> 00:34:07.570
And I was already doing
research for the book.

00:34:07.570 --> 00:34:11.219
And what I really wanted to find
out, after I had my experience,

00:34:11.219 --> 00:34:14.480
I was so close to the other side
of the veil, I wanted to know,

00:34:14.480 --> 00:34:18.080
is this my imagination, or
is there life after death?

00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:19.929
Where's the evidence for this?

00:34:19.929 --> 00:34:22.940
And so there's one
chapter in the book that

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:27.290
involves looking at what medical
science has to say about this.

00:34:27.290 --> 00:34:31.800
And the University of Virginia
Medical School has a division,

00:34:31.800 --> 00:34:34.719
and they study and they
document this kind of stuff.

00:34:34.719 --> 00:34:38.409
So I called this guy, who is a
near-death experience expert.

00:34:38.409 --> 00:34:40.130
He's a physician.

00:34:40.130 --> 00:34:42.789
And I said, hi, blah, blah,
blah, I'm working on this book.

00:34:42.789 --> 00:34:44.080
Do you think you could help me?

00:34:44.080 --> 00:34:48.320
And he said-- all my research is
online-- he goes, but why don't

00:34:48.320 --> 00:34:51.090
you talk to my colleague
who studies intersection

00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:52.860
of reincarnation and biology?

00:34:52.860 --> 00:34:55.320
It's something
really interesting.

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:58.630
And so he was literally
dropped into my lap.

00:34:58.630 --> 00:35:04.355
So there is a chapter in the
book about the intersection

00:35:04.355 --> 00:35:07.240
of reincarnation and biology,
and it's based on my interview

00:35:07.240 --> 00:35:10.650
with this physician at the
University of Virginia Medical

00:35:10.650 --> 00:35:11.430
School.

00:35:11.430 --> 00:35:14.310
And it's just really,
really, really fascinating

00:35:14.310 --> 00:35:19.750
because what they're doing is
they interview children who

00:35:19.750 --> 00:35:22.410
are born with birth
defects that are

00:35:22.410 --> 00:35:24.360
unexplained from
a medical basis.

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:27.590
But somehow, the children can
remember, in their past life,

00:35:27.590 --> 00:35:29.120
where this defect came from.

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:31.509
So for example, there's
a girl with no legs.

00:35:31.509 --> 00:35:33.550
And she'll say, oh yeah,
I got ran over by train.

00:35:33.550 --> 00:35:35.162
And they'll just say it
totally matter-of-factly, oh,

00:35:35.162 --> 00:35:36.750
in all my previous
life, just before I

00:35:36.750 --> 00:35:38.440
died, ran over by train.

00:35:38.440 --> 00:35:41.340
Or somebody who
had a deformed ear

00:35:41.340 --> 00:35:46.020
said that he was shot by
somebody that he knew.

00:35:46.020 --> 00:35:49.810
So they started going out-- team
of doctors would go to Asia,

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:51.767
and they would
record these stories,

00:35:51.767 --> 00:35:53.350
and they would
interview the children.

00:35:53.350 --> 00:35:57.055
And then they would
take the factoids

00:35:57.055 --> 00:35:58.930
that the children were
offering and then they

00:35:58.930 --> 00:36:00.697
would go compare
them against history,

00:36:00.697 --> 00:36:02.280
and they find out
that they were true.

00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:04.420
So children who were
born in one town

00:36:04.420 --> 00:36:07.390
would give you extremely
detailed descriptions

00:36:07.390 --> 00:36:09.390
of something that was
hours away to a place

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:15.470
that they had never been-- super
fascinating, super fascinating

00:36:15.470 --> 00:36:16.000
stuff.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:22.560
But your original
question was, what

00:36:22.560 --> 00:36:24.220
was missing in my
previous incarnations

00:36:24.220 --> 00:36:25.991
that I have to do this now?

00:36:25.991 --> 00:36:27.240
That's a really good question.

00:36:27.240 --> 00:36:30.330
I'll have to meditate on that.

00:36:30.330 --> 00:36:32.050
But you know, it's
a lot of challenges.

00:36:32.050 --> 00:36:33.716
It's a lot of challenges
that I've never

00:36:33.716 --> 00:36:37.760
had before-- the challenge
of how to use the mind

00:36:37.760 --> 00:36:38.710
to heal the body.

00:36:38.710 --> 00:36:41.280
That was a huge learning.

00:36:41.280 --> 00:36:44.160
The challenge of just living--

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:46.197
It's kind of like you're
in this paradox of,

00:36:46.197 --> 00:36:48.030
you want to live in
here and now because you

00:36:48.030 --> 00:36:51.727
want to really embrace
life so fully as a gift

00:36:51.727 --> 00:36:53.560
and you just want to
stay extremely present.

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:55.130
But when you have
this experience,

00:36:55.130 --> 00:36:57.390
you are reminded
that you will die.

00:36:57.390 --> 00:36:59.210
And you just want
to ask yourself,

00:36:59.210 --> 00:37:02.090
how did I live my life?

00:37:02.090 --> 00:37:04.540
So it's living in
between those two places,

00:37:04.540 --> 00:37:07.490
of living in the here and
now with a constant reminder

00:37:07.490 --> 00:37:17.360
that we're all temporal, and
that you really want to not

00:37:17.360 --> 00:37:20.370
regret and use the time wisely.

